22092023
...

I was going to start testing the card API and while looking at the required payload struct, I realised that the deck_id was mandatory but I had assumed it was optional previously. While thinking more about it, I realised that locking flashcards to one deck only is too restrictive and flashcards should be associated with many decks. This should allow users to "steal" flashcards from other users, as long as they have read access to the card.

Later on, I realised I should use a single invalidation_token again, but reuse it if it already exists - instead of using an array.

  • Switch back to single token for invalidation

POST /v1/card/
...

This initially failed when the name included a space inside, so the validation was incorrect.

Before: ```

if !field.chars().all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric()) {

After:

if !field.chars().all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || c == ' ') {

Now, there is a database error which was happening due to a missing deck_id field. After restarting the database, the request was successful. However, it was not returning the UUID, so I modified it afterwards (not in the screenshots).

GET /v1/card/{ID}
...

To test, I used the id in the previous section, from creating the card. I also forgot to register the get endpoint here. After fixing that, the endpoint worked as expected. However, while looking at the code, I realised I could implement a binary search when looking through the array of permissions, so I did with some places where I used an array.

PATCH /v1/card/{ID}
...

Worked, and updated the name as expected.


DELETE /v1/card/{{ID}}
...

Deletes the card as expected.
